elements.content: Three new polynuclear copper(II) complexes, derived from the end-on azido bridging ligand and pyridine derivatives, have been synthesized, and their crystal structures have been determined by X-ray diffraction methods; they are the dinuclear compounds [Cu2(μ1,1-N3)2(4-Etpy)4(μ-NO3)2] (1), and [Cu2(μ1,1-N3)2(3-ampy)4(μ-NO3)2]·C2H5OH (2), and the trinuclear [Cu3(μ1,1-N3)4(N3)2(Meinic)2(DMF)2] (3). 4-Etpy is 4-ethylpyridine, 3-ampy is 3-aminopyridine, and Meinic is methylisonicotinate. Compound 1, C28H36Cu2N12O6, crystallized in the monoclinic system, space group P21/n, with a = 12.355(9) Å, b = 12.474(4) Å, c = 12.854(6) Å, β = 117.68(4)°, and Z = 2. Compound 2, C22H30Cu2N16O7, crystallized in the triclinic system, space group P̄1, with a = 9.695(2) Å, b = 10.895(2) Å, c = 7.909(2) Å, α = 96.81(3)°, β = 96.40(3)°, γ = 96.56(3)° and Z = 1. Compound 3, C20H28Cu3N22O6, crystallized in the monoclinic system, space group P21/n, with a = 7.755(2) Å, b = 14.680(5) Å, c = 15.810(5) Å, β = 102.81(2)°, and Z = 2. 1−3 have the symmetric [Cu(μ1,1-N3)2Cu]2+ core and structural parameters outside the previously reported range. Magnetic susceptibility data, measured from 2 to 300 K, show strong ferromagnetic coupling for the dinuclear end-on compounds 1 and 2 and bulk moderate ferromagnetic coupling for the trinuclear compound 3. These data were fitted to the appropriate equations derived from the Hamiltonian H = −J S 1 S 2 for 1 and 2 and from the Hamiltonian H = −J 1 (S A1 S B + S A2 S B) − J 2 S A1·S A2 for 3, giving the parameters J = 230.1(1) cm-1, g = 2.17(0.01) for 1, J = 223.2(2) cm-1, g = 2.16(0.01) for 2, and J 1 = 47.3(2) cm-1, J 2 = −22.5(1) cm-1, g A = 2.26(0.02), g B = 2.07(0.03) for 3. The magnetic susceptibility data can be correlated with the structural parameters.

Introduction

Recently, there has been great interest in the magnetic coupling in end-on (EO) azido-bridged copper(II) complexes with the [Cu(μ1,1-N3)2Cu]2+ core stimulated by the determination of the spin distribution in the spin triplet ground state in the previously published compound [Cu2(μ1,1-N3)2(t-Buty)4](ClO4)2 (t-Buty = p-tert-butylpyridine) and by the publication of two theoretical papers studying the effect of the structural parameters (Cu-N(azido) distance, mean Cu-N-Cu angle (θ), and mean out-of plane deviation of the azido group (τ)) on the exchange coupling constants of complexes of this kind. Previously, the study of dinuclear copper(II) compounds involving a combination of a μ1,2-diazine and a μ1,1-N3 azide bridge had provided support for antiferromagnetic exchange of the μ1,1-N3 azide bridge at Cu-N-Cu angles exceeding 108°.

Here, with the aim of increasing the structural and magnetic data for the end-on azido-bridged copper(II) complexes, we present the syntheses and the structural and magnetic study of two new dinuclear compounds with the above-mentioned structure:  [Cu2(μ1,1-N3)2(4-Etpy)4(μ-NO3)2] (1) and [Cu2(μ1,1-N3)2(3-ampy)4(μ-NO3)2]·C2H5OH (2). 4-Etpy is 4-ethylpyridine and 3-ampy is 3-aminopyridine. 1 and 2 present θ angles outside of the previously reported values (98.2(2) and 97.5(1)° for 1 and 2, respectively). Also, 1 and 2 present τ angles outside of the previously reported values (31.3(2) and 35.6(2)° for 1 and 2, respectively). The variable temperature magnetic susceptibility measurements of 1 and 2 indicate strong ferromagnetic coupling.

 Physical Measurements. IR spectra were recorded on a Nicolet 520 FT-IR spectrometer. The crystallographic data, the conditions retained for the intensity data collection, and some features of the structure refinements are listed in Table . Graphite-monochromatized Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.710 69 Å) with the ω-scan technique was used to collect the data sets. The accurate unit-cell parameters were determined from automatic centering of 40 reflections (6.0° < θ < 13.0°) for 1, 24 reflections (7.7° < θ < 12.6°) for 2, and 24 reflections (7.0° < θ < 14.0°) for 3 and refined by least-squares methods. A total of 4116 reflections (3371 independent reflections, R int = 0.0336) for 1, 2982 reflections (2771 independent reflections, R int = 0.0259) for 2, and 4361 reflections (3625 independent reflections, R int = 0.0427) for 3 were collected in the range 3.12° < θ < 27.99°, 3.02° < θ < 25.00°, and 2.77° < θ < 26.98° for 1, 2, and 3, respectively. Intensity decays of 6%, 3%, and 3% for control reflections (−1 4 −1; −1 2 1; 0 4 2), (1 −2 1; 2 −1 1; 4 0 0), and (1 1 4; −1 −2 −1; 2 2 −2) for 1, 2, and 3, respectively, measured after every set of 100 reflections, were observed during data collection. Corrections were applied for Lorentz polarization effects, for intensity decay, and for absorption using the DIFABS computer program. The structures were solved by direct methods using the SHELXS-86 computer program and refined by full-matrix least-squares methods on F 2, using the SHELXL-93 program incorporated in the SHELXTL/PC, version 5.03, program library and the graphics program PLUTON. All non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically. The hydrogen atoms were obtained from ΔF maps and subsequently fixed geometrically with the HFIX utility. In the case of 2, two split orientations with 50% occupancy, related by an inversion center, were introduced for the atoms of disordered lattice solvent molecule (EtOH). For 1, 2, and 3, respectively, the final R indices for all observed reflections are 0.0561, 0.0499, and 0.0481 and the number of refined parameters are 224, 244, and 243. The maximum and minimum peaks in the final difference Fourier synthesis are respectively 0.53 and −0.43 e Å-3 for 1, 0.64 and −0.62 e Å-3 for 2, and 0.37 and −0.66 e Å-3 for 3. Significant bond parameters are reported in Tables −4.

The IR absorption bands observed in the spectrum of the complex at 3429 (vs), 3326 (s), and 3218 (s) cm-1 are tentatively assigned to the vibrational modes of free EtOH and are superimposed on those of the amino group. The asymmetric stretch mode of the azide appears as a very strong band at 2080 cm-1. The band at 1277 cm-1 may be assigned to the nitrate group mixed with the symmetric stretching mode of the azide ligand, suggesting asymmetric μ-1,1 azide bridging. The bands at 1493 (s), 1454 (s), and 1317 (vs) cm-1 suggest the bidentate chelating nitrato ligand. The electronic spectrum of the solid complex exhibits a very strong band centered around 415 nm and a distinct absorption band of moderate intensity around 540 nm, as found for other copper(II) azide complexes containing μ-1,1 N3 groups, assigned to the N3 CuII CT transitions. The d−d band appears as a broad band centered around 630 nm.

Magnetic Results. The variable temperature magnetic susceptibility data for 1−3 were recorded between 300 and 2 K. Plots of χM T versus T for 1 and 2 are shown in Figure . For 1 the χM T value at room temperature (1.06 cm3 mol-1 K) increases to a maximum at 44 K (1.17 cm3 mol-1 K) as temperature decreases, indicating a strong ferromagnetic coupling, and after the maximum, it decreases to 1.08 cm3 mol-1 K at 2 K. For 2 the χM T value at room temperature (1.05 cm3 mol-1 K) increases to a maximum at 82 K (1.14 cm3mol-1K) as the temperature decreases, also indicating a strong ferromagnetic coupling, and after the maximum it decreases to 0.66 cm3 mol-1 K at 2 K. The susceptibility data for 1 and 2 were fitted to the Bleaney−Bowers expression for the magnetic susceptibility of isotropically coupled S = 1/2 dinuclear compounds, derived from the Hamiltonian H = −J S 1 S 2:  χ = {2Ng 2β2/[k(T − ω)]}{exp[−J/(kT)]}. The Weiss ω parameter was introduced in the formula to take into account possible antiferromagnetic interactions between dinuclear molecules together with zero-field splitting in the S = 1 ground state. The results of the best fit, shown as the solid lines in Figure , were J = 230.1(1) cm-1, g = 2.17(0.01), ω = −0.17(0.01) K for 1 and J = 223.2(2) cm-1, g = 2.16(0.01), ω = −1.40(0.01) K for 2. These calculated J values are the strongest spin triplet ground state−spin singlet state separation reported to date for copper(II) compounds with the symmetrical [Cu(μ1,1-N3)2Cu]2+ core. According to Ruiz et al., from density functional calculations there appears to be a clear correlation between the calculated J parameter and the θ angle; the J value decreases from a maximum at about θ = 85° with increasing θ, eventually reaching an antiferromagnetic regime for θ ≥ 104°. The τ angle seems to have a negligible influence on the J value. Also, from the linear trend (J = −41.94θ + 4440 cm-1) in the θ vs J plot observed by Thomson et al.; the predicted J values are 321.5 and 350.8 cm-1 for 1 and 2, respectively. Note that 1 and 2 have the lowest reported θ angles (98.2(1) and 97.5(1)°, respectively) and the highest J values (230.1(1) and 223.2(2) cm-1, respectively). The τ values are the highest reported so far (31.3(2) and 35.6(2)° for 1 and 2, respectively); the large J values measured here confirm the negligible effect of τ on J. The Cu−N found distances in 1 and 2 are in the range of the previously reported parameters.

elements.content: The magnetic susceptibility data, χMT versus T for 3 are plotted in Figure . For 3 the χM T value of 1.42 cm3 mol-1 K at room temperature increases slowly to 1.7 cm3mol-1K at 6 K as the temperature decreases, and it increases quickly to 1.96 cm3 mol-1 K at 2 K. The magnetic susceptibility behavior of 3 indicates bulk ferromagnetic coupling. Taking into account the linear structure of 3 (Scheme ), the fit of the magnetic data was made by using the appropriate equation derived from the Hamiltonian H = −J 1 (S A1 S B + S A2 S B) − J 2 S A1·S A2. The best-fit parameters were J 1 = 47.3(2) cm-1, J 2 = −22.5(1) cm-1, g A = 2.26(0.02), g B = 2.07(0.03). In 3 the θ angles are 100.8(2)° for Cu(1)−N(11)−Cu(2) and 99.2° for Cu(1)−N(21)−Cu(2). The ferromagnetic coupling in the [Cu(μ1,1-N3)2Cu]2+ core (J 1 = 47.5 cm-1) is in accordance with θ ≤ 104°. The antiferromagnetic coupling between the terminal Cu(II) atoms is more difficult to explain, but recently, from a theoretical density functional study, Ruiz et al. have predicted a moderate AF coupling between terminal Cu(II) atoms in trinuclear Cu(II) compounds with oxo bridges and ferromagnetic coupling between neighboring Cu(II) atoms. We have not considered the possible AF interaction through 1,3 azido bridges connecting the neighboring trinuclear units because in an octahedral environment the unpaired electronic density on d z 2 atomic orbitals of the Cu(II) ions is negligible. The absence of AF interaction between the trimeric units is also confirmed by the χM T vs T plot; no decay of the χM T value is observed even at 2 K.

Conclusions

Kahn et al. concluded their previously cited paper1 with a question: "Can the 1,1-azido group be considered as an almost universal ferromagnetic coupler, or is the stabilization of the parallel spin state only achieved in a limiting range of bridging angle values?" From the density functional study of Ruiz et al. the answer is the second possibility; for θ ≥ 104° it is possible to have AF coupling. Also, Thomson et al., after the magneto-structural study of several dinuclear copper(II) compounds involving a combination of a μ1,2-diazine and a μ1,1-N3 azide bridges, suggest that the realm of the ferromagnetic coupling ceases for Cu-N-Cu angles greater than 108°.

elements.content: In this paper we have presented the synthesis and the structural and magnetic study of two new symmetrical [ Cu(μ1,1-N3)2Cu]2+ complexes [Cu2(μ1,1-N3)2(4-Etpy)4(μ-NO3)2] (1) and [Cu2(μ1,1-N3)2(3-ampy)4(μ-NO3)2]·C2H5OH (2), which present the lowest reported θ angles:  98.3(2) and 97.5(1)° for 1 and 2, respectively, with the strongest calculated J values of 230.1 and 223.2 cm-1 for 1 and 2 respectively. These results are in accordance with the above-mentioned predictions for the lower θ region, but they remain to be confirmed experimentally in the higher θ region. To our knowledge, the copper(II) complex with the symmetrical [Cu(μ1,1-N3)2Cu]2+ core (or having as the bridge only one μ1,1-N3 ligand and short Cu−N(azido distances)) and θ angles greater than 104−108° has not yet been synthesized.

(a) [Cu 2 ( μ 1,1 -N 3 ) 2 (4-Etpy) 4 ( μ -NO 3 ) 2 ] (1). Copper(II) nitrate trihydrate (0.72 g, 3 mmol) and 4-ethylpyridine (0,75 g, 7 mmol) were mixed in 40 cm3 of acetone. An aqueous solution (5 cm3) of NaN3 (0.39 g, 6 mmol) was added to this mixture with continuous stirring. DMF was then added to dissolve any precipitate, and the final clear solution mixture was allowed to stand in a desiccator containing a beaker filled with diethyl ether until good quality crystals formed. Yield ca. 45% (with respect to copper). Anal. Calcd for C28H36Cu2N12O6:  C, 44.0; H, 4.8; N, 22.0; Cu, 16.6. Found:  C, 44.0; H, 4.6; N, 21.7; Cu, 16.3.

(b) [Cu 2 ( μ 1,1 -N 3 ) 2 (3-ampy) 4 ( μ -NO 3 ) 2 ]·C 2 H 5 OH (2). An ethanol solution of 3-aminopyridine (0.58 g, 8 mmol) was added to Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.72 g, 3 mmol) dissolved in ethanol (20 cm3). Upon dropwise addition of NaN3 (0.32 g, 5 mmol) dissolved in 5 cm3 of water, a precipitate was obtained. DMF was then added to the heterogeneous mixture until there was complete dissolution of the precipitate. The final solution mixture was filtered and allowed to stand in a refrigerator for ca. two months until small black crystals of the complex formed. Yield ca. 50% (with respect to copper). Anal. Calcd for C22H30Cu2N16O7:  C, 34.9; H, 4.0; N, 29.6; Cu, 16.8. Found:  C, 34.7; H, 3.9; N, 29.9; Cu, 16.7.

(c) [Cu 3 ( μ 1,1 -N 3 ) 4 (N 3 ) 2 (Meinic) 2 (DMF) 2 ] (3). Copper(II) nitrate trihydrate (0.72 g, 3 mmol) and methyl isonicotinate (1.10 g, 8 mmol) were mixed together in acetone (30 cm3) followed by dropwise addition of an aqueous solution (5 cm3) of NaN3 (0.39 g, 6 mmol) until an olive-green precipitate was formed. DMF was then added until the precipitate disssolved. The clear solution mixture was then boiled for about 15 min and allowed to stand in an open beaker for several weeks to deposit black, well-formed crystals of the complex. Yield:  20% (with respect to copper). Anal. Calcd for C20H28Cu3N22O6:  C, 27.8; H, 3.3; N, 35.7; Cu, 22.1. Found, C 27.6, H, 3.2; N, 35.5; Cu, 22.0.
